How we get paid

We want this to be a “win-win” situation. So we only want to get paid if we bring you value in the form of finding a personal finance option that works for you. Not by selling your data. Credible receives compensation when we help you find the best product from one of our lending partners. The amount of our compensation does not impact how and where lenders appear on our site, and Credible charges you no fees of any sort. Some lenders may take traffic sources into account when offering credit terms.

TABLE OF CONTENTS

    Why refinance student loans?

    Refinancing student loans can be a smart way to secure a better interest rate, and refinancing private student loans can help you save without losing federal protections. To make the process easier, we've reviewed and compared the best student loan refinance companies so you can quickly find the right fit.

    Here's how refinancing might help you take control of your finances:

    • Lower your interest rate: If your credit and income have improved since you borrowed, you might qualify for a lower rate, potentially saving thousands of dollars in interest.
    • Reduce your monthly payment: Extending your loan term when refinancing student loans can lower your monthly payment, freeing up money in your budget.
    • Pay off debt faster: Choosing a shorter loan term helps you pay off your student loan faster, and you'll pay less interest overall.
    • Simplify your payments: Refinancing allows you to combine multiple loans into one, making repayment easier to manage.
    • Remove a cosigner: If your credit has improved, refinancing can help you release a cosigner from responsibility for your loan.

    When to refinance student loans

    Refinancing isn't the best choice for everyone, but it can make a big difference in the right circumstances.

    Consider refinancing if:

    • You have private student loans: Private loans aren't eligible for federal programs, so refinancing private student loans won't cost you federal benefits.
    • You qualify for a lower rate: If market rates have dropped or your credit has improved, refinancing may help you secure a better deal.
    • You want to change your loan term: Choose a longer term to reduce your monthly payment, or a shorter one to save on interest.
    • You have stable income: A steady job and good credit will improve your chances of qualifying for top rates.

    When not to refinance student loans

    Hold off on refinancing if:

    • You rely on federal loan benefits: Refinancing federal loans into a private loan makes you ineligible for income-driven repayment plans, forbearance, deferment, and forgiveness programs.
    • You're not financially stable: If your income or credit score is low, you might not qualify for favorable rates and might even end up paying more.
    • Your current loans offer compelling benefits: Some loans come with perks like autopay discounts or loyalty rewards that you may lose if you refinance.

    Refinancing student loans pros and cons

    Pros

    • Lower interest rates
    • Smaller monthly payments
    • Faster debt payoff
    • Simplified repayment
    • Cosigner release

    Cons

    • Loss of federal loan benefits
    • Eligibility may be limited with no degree
    • Requires strong credit and income
    • May lose grace or deferment periods
    • Cosigner may still be needed

    How to refinance student loans and compare student loan refinance rates with Credible

    Refinancing and finding the best student loan refinance rates through Credible is fast and easy:

    1. Find your student loan refinancing rates

    Get prequalified in minutes with a soft credit check. You'll see real, personalized rates from top lenders with fixed APRs from 3.99% to 10.15%, and variable APRs from 3.84% to 11.41%.

    2. Compare your refinancing options

    Evaluate student loan refinancing lenders side by side, considering not just rates, but also repayment terms and monthly payments. None of Credible's partner lenders charge origination fees or prepayment penalties.

    3. Choose a loan

    Select the student loan refinancing option that best fits your financial goals. You may choose to apply with a cosigner to improve your chances of approval or secure better terms.

    4. Submit your student loan refinancing application

    Complete the lender's full student loan refinancing application and upload supporting documents such as pay stubs and tax returns.

    What types of loans are eligible to be refinanced?

    Borrowers commonly refinance private student loans, but refinancing student loans can also include federal loans — with important trade-offs to consider.

    You can refinance most federal and private student loans, including:

    • Undergraduate and graduate loans
    • Medical school loans, including those with deferment through residency
    • MBA loans
    • Law school loans, including bar study loans

    Keep in mind that refinancing federal loans turns them into private loans, which means you'll lose access to federal repayment programs and protections.

    How to choose the right lender for refinancing student loans

    Choosing the right lender depends on your financial situation and goals. When comparing the top student loan refinancing lenders, look at:

    • Interest rates (fixed vs. variable)
    • Loan terms
    • Fees (Credible's partners don't charge origination or prepayment fees)
    • Repayment options, including deferment or forbearance
    • Cosigner policies

    Credible lets you compare personalized, prequalified offers from trusted lenders, including Earnest, SoFi, Citizens, ELFI, and more.

    Is student loan refinancing the same as student loan consolidation?

    Student loan refinancing and student loan consolidation might sound like the same thing. However, they are not, and it's important to understand the difference:

    • When you refinance student loans, you replace your existing debt with a new private loan, ideally from one of the best student loan refinance companies, at a lower interest rate that matches your financial goals. While you may qualify for a lower rate or a new term, refinancing federal loans means giving up federal protections.
    • Student loan consolidation is when you combine multiple federal loans into a Direct Consolidation Loan through the federal government, not a private lender. The rate is the weighted average of your existing rates. You retain federal benefits but won't save on interest.

    Student loan refinancing and student loan consolidation are often used interchangeably. However, understanding the difference is crucial because confusing the two could lead to unexpected trade-offs, like losing federal protections or missing out on potential interest savings.

    FAQ

    Should I refinance my student loans?

    View

    Refinancing student loans can be a good option if you qualify for a lower interest rate, want to change your loan term, or need to simplify repayment. It’s often most beneficial for private student loans, since refinancing federal student loans means giving up access to income-driven repayment, forbearance, deferment, and forgiveness programs.

    What is the best student loan refinance option for me?

    View

    The best lender to refinance student loans depends on factors such as your credit profile, loan amount, and whether you want fixed or variable rates.

    What are the best student loan refinance rates right now?

    View

    The lowest fixed-rate student loan refinancing APRs available on Credible currently start at 3.99%, with variable-rate APRs starting as low as 3.84%. The rates you're offered will depend on factors including your credit score, income, and whether you're applying with a cosigner. Shopping around helps ensure you're seeing the most competitive rates for your profile and the best opportunities to refinance student loans.

    Can I refinance only some of my student loans?

    View

    You can refinance all of your student loans, or just a portion of them. For example, you might refinance only your private loans, while maintaining your federal loans to preserve benefits like income-driven repayment or forgiveness options.

    Which lenders offer the best student loan refinance rates?

    View

    The top student loan refinancing lenders offer rates based on factors like your credit score, income, loan balance, and whether you apply with a cosigner. Many refinancing options available through Credible consistently offer some of the lowest fixed and variable rates in the market to highly qualified borrowers.
     

    Does refinancing student loans hurt my credit?

    View

    Refinancing may slightly reduce your credit score temporarily due to the hard credit check and closing of the old account. However, building a history of on-time payments on your new loan can improve your credit over time.

    Can I refinance private loans to get lower student loan refi rates?

    View

    You can refinance private student loans, federal student loans, or both. Many borrowers choose to refinance only private loans so they can keep federal loans and their benefits, such as income-driven repayment or forgiveness programs. Comparing offers from multiple lenders helps you find the best student loan refinance rates available. 

    How to lower student loan payments without refinancing?

    View

    One way to understand how to lower student loan payments without refinancing is to look at options your current lender or servicer offers. Some provide temporary interest-only payments, hardship forbearance, or payment extension programs. Reviewing your repayment plan and contacting your servicer are the best first steps to learn how to lower your student loan payments using your existing loan terms.

    How can I reduce my total student loan cost?

    View

    You can reduce your total cost by refinancing your student loans to secure a lower interest rate. Getting the best student loan refinance rates available to you can decrease your interest costs, potentially saving you money each month and over the life of the loan.

    How can I remove student loans from my credit report?

    View

    Student loans stay on your credit report for as long as they are open and active, and accurate information about them cannot be removed. However, refinancing your student loans can replace one or more existing loans with a new loan, which will be reported as a new account and show the old accounts as paid in full.

    Can I refinance my private student loans if I have bad credit?

    View

    It's possible to refinance student loans with bad credit, but you'll likely have to pay higher rates. Applying with a creditworthy cosigner can boost your chances of approval. Some student loan refinance lenders also offer cosigner release options after a period of on-time payments.

    Can I refinance a student loan more than once?

    View

    You can refinance student loans as many times as you want. People often refinance student loans multiple times if they qualify for better rates or want to change their repayment terms.

    How long does it take to refinance a student loan?

    View

    Student loan refinancing applications can take anywhere from a few days to several weeks to process. You can expedite this by submitting all required documents promptly and responding to lender inquiries in a timely manner.

    Is it worth refinancing to get the best student loan refinance rates?

    View

    If you're wondering, 'Can I refinance student loans and actually save?', the answer is often yes. It can be worthwhile if you qualify for a lower student loan refi rate or need to reduce your monthly payments. You could significantly cut your monthly costs or total interest paid if you refinance student loans at a lower interest rate or an extended loan term.

    How can I qualify and refinance student loans to get the best rates?

    View

    To qualify for student loan refinancing, lenders typically require a credit score of around 670 or higher, along with a steady and verifiable income, and a low debt-to-income ratio. They'll also consider the details of your existing loans, such as your remaining balances and the schools you attended. If you don't meet the qualifications on your own, applying with a creditworthy cosigner can increase your chances of approval.
